The best approach for `File.*` and `Directory.*` is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already covers your exact API surface. No need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install the packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs or Startup.cs:
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
// MockFileSystem also supports Directory.Exists out of the box
mockFs.AddDirectory("/data");

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/config.json"));
Assert.True(manager.EnsureDirectory("/data"));
```

**Why this over a custom wrapper?** `System.IO.Abstractions` covers the entire `System.IO` surface (`File`, `Directory`, `Path`, `Stream`, etc.), so you won't need to extend it as you find more statics. The `MockFileSystem` gives you an in-memory filesystem for free — no mocking framework needed.

Once you've added the package and DI registration, you can use the **`migrate-static-to-wrapper`** skill to bulk-replace all the `File.*`/`Directory.*` call sites across your project. Just say the word!
